ASSIGNMENT
1.	Testing and Types of Testing
Process of evaluating software to make sure it works correctly, meets requirements and it is bug free
Manual testing – Performed by humans without automation tool, good for small projects.
Automation testing – Uses tools or scripts to execute test, ideal for large scale testing
FUNCTIONAL TESTING
Verifies features are working correctly, Matches business requirements.
•	Login button works 
•	User can place an order 
•	Payment is successful
Examples:
•	Unit Testing 
•	Integration Testing 
•	System Testing 
•	User Acceptance Testing (UAT) 
•	Smoke Testing 
•	Sanity Testing 
•	Regression Testing 
NON-FUNCTIONAL TESTING
Focuses on performance, speed, security, usability
•	Website loads fast 
•	App works with many users at once 
•	Data is secure
Examples:
•	Performance Testing (Load, Stress) 
•	Security Testing 
•	Usability Testing 
•	Compatibility Testing 
•	Reliability Testing 
•	Scalability Testing

2. Smoke, Regression, Sanity, Unit testing.
•	Unit testing – Small part of code is tested 
•	Smoke testing – Test to verify main functionalities of an application is working fine, ensure build is stable before detailed testing
•	Regression testing – Ensures overall application is still stable after any change.
•	Sanity testing – It is done after minor changes or bug fix to verify that the fix works and nothing around it is broken

3. SDLC - part of developer or programmer
It is the process to build a software from start to end
•	Requirement
→ What to build 
•	Design
→ How it will look/work 
•	Development
→ Coding the application 
•	Testing
→ Checking for bugs 
•	Deployment
→ Releasing to users 
•	Maintenance
→ Fixing issues & updates 

4. STLC - part of developer or programmer
It is the process testers follow to test a software
•	Understand Requirements
→ What needs to be tested 
•	Plan Testing
→ How to test, tools, timeline 
•	Write Test Cases
→ Steps to test features 
•	Execute Tests
→ Run the test cases 
•	Report Bugs
→ Log defects if something fails 
•	Close Testing
→ Testing completed

5. Bug/Defect life cycle
•	New → Bug is created and logged 
•	Assigned → Bug is given to a developer 
•	Open → Developer starts working on it 
•	Fixed → Developer fixes the bug 
•	Retest → Tester checks the fix 
•	Verified → Bug is confirmed as fixed 
•	Closed → Bug is closed successfully
•	Reopened → Bug still exists after fix 
•	Rejected → Not a valid bug 
•	Deferred → Fix is postponed to later

6. Severity and Priority
Severity and Priority are used to decide how important a bug is.
Severity means how serious the bug is (impact on system), Decided by QA/Testers
•	App crash → High Severity 
•	Small UI issue → Low Severity 
Priority means how quickly the bug should be fixed (urgency), Decided by Product Manager / Team
•	Login issue → High Priority 
•	Minor typo → Low Priority
